data.text:
If "j'y suis" means "I get it" and "jamais" means "never" and "alle" means "went" then what does "j'y suis jamais alle" mean? it's the title of a song I've bene trying to figure out but I always come up with something that makes no sense.

titania8080 said:

If "j'y suis" means "I get it" and "jamais" means "never" and "alle" means "went" then what does "j'y suis jamais alle" mean? it's the title of a song I've bene trying to figure out but I always come up with something that makes no sense.

Hi Titania and welcome

Yes "j'y suis" means "I get it" but that's a set phrase (literally "I'm there"). This is just the normal meaning of the words so "j'y suis jamais all√©" is literally "I there am never gone" (the normal way of saying it in French) so "I have never gone there" or better still "I have never been there". Cheers, Tim.
